node.text:
Every year, people say “never forget,” and every year I think, “I couldn’t forget if I tried.” It was 8:45am when I heard the rattle of my apartment window. Being from Los Angeles, my body instinctively thought it was an Earthquake, but what it actually was… that was unimaginable. A plane had flown right by my apartment, and right into the World Trade Center. I immediately called my mother to tell her not to worry if she saw something on the news about a crash. Everything was fine, and I was safe and sound. I was rushing to get off the phone because it was fashion week, and I worked for Donna Karan in the PR office. I explained to my mom that our show started soon, and I needed to get to the tents… she gently told me that the show would likely be cancelled. Exasperated, I told her that the show was in *midtown* and the crash happened *downtown* - literally worlds away in New York City geography! 

Of course she was right. The second plane hit 15 minutes later. At 19, I didn’t know how much the world would change that day, and how my world would change along with it.

My roommate and I ran to the closest store to buy food and water. We were so young and had no idea what to do.. I remember we showed up at the register with a jar of pickles and Oreo ice cream cones, but no ice cream. Panic is really something. We made it to the sidewalk right as the first building fell. I’ll spare you the details of what we saw and heard because that’s the stuff I’ve been trying to forget for 20 years.

We ran around frantically trying to locate friends, trying to secure a safe place to stay, trying to call our parents. I was still in my fashion show dress, but had at least put on sneakers. 

At the end of the day, we were a huddled group of friends in one apartment. Half of us covered in dust and ash, most of us without homes to return to, and all of us completely traumatized. 

The days that followed were the bleakest of all. I’ll spare you those details too, because I think those might be what haunts me the most. The dark aftermath, and the feeling that it might never end. (continued in comments)….
